---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="Menden Lab | Research"
	description="Research themes at the Menden Lab spanning computational biomedicine and translational pharmacogenomics."
>
	<section class="hero-card">
		<p class="eyebrow">Research</p>
		<h1 class="headline">From computational cancer pharmacogenomics to translational precision medicine.</h1>
		<p class="lead">
			The lab's public research profile frames a coherent programme: develop statistically sound,
			machine-learning-guided methods for complex biomedical data, then use those methods to
			explain disease heterogeneity, predict response, and support better therapeutic decisions.
		</p>
	</section>

	<section class="grid-two">
		<article class="content-card">
			<h2>Computational Cancer Pharmacogenomics</h2>
			<p>
				A major strength of the lab is computational method development for monotherapy,
				combination therapy, CRISPR lethality, and drug-resistance screens. The goal is to
				predict sensitivity and synergy while identifying genomic and molecular biomarkers that
				remain useful in clinically realistic settings.
			</p>
		</article>
		<article class="content-card">
			<h2>Translational Computational Pharmacogenomics</h2>
			<p>
				The lab extends its pharmacogenomics framework beyond cancer into tuberculosis drug
				resistance, inflammatory skin disease, neurodegenerative disease, and diabetes. Across
				these projects, the emphasis stays the same: integrate rich data, stratify meaningful
				subgroups, and accelerate precision medicine.
			</p>
		</article>
		<article class="content-card compact-list">
			<h2>Methods and Platforms</h2>
			<ul>
				<li>Biostatistics and interpretable machine learning</li>
				<li>High-throughput pharmacogenomic and CRISPR screening analysis</li>
				<li>Multi-omics integration and clinically grounded biomarker modelling</li>
				<li>Patient and disease-model stratification from deep molecular profiles</li>
			</ul>
		</article>
		<article class="content-card compact-list">
			<h2>Examples of Lab Themes</h2>
			<ul>
				<li>Ancestry-aware analysis of cancer cell line drug response</li>
				<li>AI in early drug discovery and biomarker prioritisation</li>
				<li>Intrinsic drug resistance and rare-resistance marker discovery</li>
				<li>Clinical translatability and microenvironment-aware modelling</li>
			</ul>
		</article>
		<article class="content-card compact-list">
			<h2>Collaborative Setting</h2>
			<p>
				The public lab descriptions position the group as highly collaborative, adapting methods
				to disease-specific knowledge from partner groups, literature, and data-driven analysis.
				That makes this research page a good place to later add institutional collaborators,
				consortia, and project pages.
			</p>
		</article>
		<article class="content-card compact-list">
			<h2>Representative Publications Mentioned in the Public Lab Profile</h2>
			<ul>
				<li>Pharmacogenomic agreement between major cancer cell line datasets</li>
				<li>A landscape of pharmacogenomic interactions in cancer</li>
				<li>The germline genetic component of drug sensitivity in cancer cell lines</li>
				<li>AI in early drug discovery enabling precision medicine</li>
			</ul>
		</article>
		<article class="content-card">
			<h2>Why This Matters</h2>
			<p>
				The through-line across the lab's programme is not just prediction accuracy. It is the
				ability to turn heterogeneous biomedical data into clinically useful hypotheses, more
				robust biomarkers, and better-targeted interventions.
			</p>
		</article>
	</section>

	<section class="grid-two" aria-label="Research summary">
		<article class="content-card">
			<h2>Research Focus</h2>
			<p>
				The lab builds computational methods that connect deep molecular characterisation,
				disease biology, and treatment response. A central goal is to move from high-dimensional
				data toward clinically interpretable predictions and actionable biomarkers.
			</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Drug sensitivity, synergy, and resistance modelling</li>
				<li>Biomarker discovery and patient stratification</li>
				<li>Translational computational pharmacogenomics across disease areas</li>
			</ul>
		</article>
		<article class="content-card compact-list">
			<h2>Open Science and Software</h2>
			<p>
				The public `MendenLab` GitHub organisation highlights the lab's emphasis on reusable
				computational tools and project-based research outputs. Recent public repositories span
				foundational methods, translational modelling, and applied biomedical analysis.
			</p>
			<ul>
				<li>`DT-GPT` for model-driven biomedical workflows</li>
				<li>`TwinWeaver` for converting EHR data into LLM-ingestible text</li>
				<li>Applied repositories across oncology, proteomics, and disease endotypes</li>
			</ul>
		</article>
	</section>

	<section class="grid-two">
		<article class="content-card compact-list">
			<h2>Selected Highlights</h2>
			<p>
				The current lab profile emphasizes computational cancer pharmacogenomics, clinically
				grounded biomarker modelling, and AI-enabled drug discovery. The Munich group page also
				highlights an ERC Starting Grant and work on ancestry-aware drug response, resistance
				modelling, and translational pharmacogenomics beyond cancer.
			</p>
			<ul>
				<li>Precision medicine through clinically informed modelling</li>
				<li>High-throughput drug screen and CRISPR screen analysis</li>
				<li>Expansion into tuberculosis, skin disease, Parkinson's disease, and diabetes</li>
			</ul>
		</article>
		<article class="content-card compact-list">
			<h2>What This Prototype Already Supports</h2>
			<ul>
				<li>A research-led landing page that can be hosted on GitHub Pages</li>
				<li>An expandable people section with one profile page per team member</li>
				<li>A publications page for selected papers and future filtering</li>
				<li>Simple migration later from your personal repository to `MendenLab`</li>
			</ul>
		</article>
	</section>
</Layout>
